---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import ThreeColumnLayout from "../layouts/ThreeColumnLayout.astro";
import Ornament from "../components/Ornament.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="About">
  <ThreeColumnLayout>
    <article>
      <h1>About Chris Busse</h1>
      <p class="meta-text">Technology Leader · Speaker · Writer</p>
      <p>
        I use creativity to guide business, product, and technology leaders through
        complex high-risk enterprise change journeys.
      </p>
      <p>
        For over thirty years, that work has taken many forms. Today it means leading
        Enterprise Client Solutions and AI at SingleStone, where I help consulting
        clients navigate architecture modernization, AI strategy, and domain-driven
        design. I also founded Eszett, where I help artists who reject AI in their
        art leverage it to better position and sell their work.
      </p>
      <Ornament glyph="☙" />
      <p>
        Before that I served as Chief Digital Officer and VP of Delivery at Terazo,
        where I built the firm's Twilio practice and spoke at SIGNAL four times.
        Earlier, I co-founded APIvista, an API strategy consultancy, and delivered
        a keynote at the Nordic APIs Platform Summit in Stockholm. At Capital One,
        I led the launch of DevExchange&mdash;the first public API platform from a
        North American bank&mdash;and founded the API Craft RVA meetup.
      </p>
      <p>
        I've spoken at SXSW Interactive, Nordic APIs, Twilio SIGNAL, APIStrat, and
        dozens of other events over the past fifteen years. My talks explore enterprise
        modernization, API strategy, developer experience, and AI transformation.
      </p>
      <p>
        Based in Richmond, Virginia.
      </p>
      <Ornament glyph="☙" />
      <h2 id="on-process">On Process</h2>
      <p>
        Much of the writing and code on this site is developed with AI assistance,
        primarily Claude by Anthropic. I treat AI as a collaborator in the same way
        a journalist works with an editor or a researcher works with a librarian:
        the tool extends my reach, but the accountability is mine.
      </p>
      <p>
        The degree of AI involvement varies. Some pieces begin as broad research
        prompts where the AI surfaces sources and synthesizes background material
        that I then shape into an argument. Others are pair-written through iterative
        conversation, with the AI drafting and me directing. Some I write entirely
        myself. The site itself&mdash;its templates, components, and styling&mdash;was
        built collaboratively with AI as well.
      </p>
      <p>
        Where AI contributed meaningfully to a piece, I disclose it in the article's
        metadata and process colophon. I do this not because the norms require it
        yet&mdash;they are still forming&mdash;but because I believe transparency
        about process is a prerequisite for trust. The words published under my name
        reflect my judgment, my editorial choices, and my willingness to stand behind
        them. How they were produced is something you deserve to know.
      </p>
    </article>
  </ThreeColumnLayout>
</BaseLayout>
